17
00:01:24,987 --> 00:01:27,409
Okay, so Astro Bot Rescue Mission, it's a VR platformer.

18
00:01:27,509 --> 00:01:29,452
It was released last October for PSVR,

19
00:01:29,512 --> 00:01:31,974
and it was Asobi Team's first commercial title.

20
00:01:32,835 --> 00:01:33,616
So if you'll allow me today,

21
00:01:33,636 --> 00:01:34,998
we're gonna, I'd like to take you on a journey

22
00:01:35,698 --> 00:01:37,480
and show you how we got around to making this game.

23
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:38,662
There's quite a lot of content,

24
00:01:38,682 --> 00:01:40,123
so I'm going to be going quite fast.

25
00:01:40,724 --> 00:01:41,765
If I end up speaking too fast

26
00:01:41,805 --> 00:01:42,886
and you can't understand what I'm saying,

27
00:01:42,906 --> 00:01:45,329
just, you know, wave and we'll get there.

28
00:01:46,190 --> 00:01:50,993
So a little bit, before we go on that journey, I just want to rewind a tiny bit and introduce a little bit about myself.

29
00:01:51,074 --> 00:01:58,119
So I grew up in the south of France in the 80s, and my youth was pretty much made up of nature, organic things,

30
00:01:58,259 --> 00:02:05,064
and a lot of Japanese anime, and of course a lot of video games, like you guys I'm sure, you know, from both America, but with a strong influence from Japan.

31
00:02:06,637 --> 00:02:12,240
At 18 I moved to UK, I began a career in games, I worked as a QA, a tester, for companies

32
00:02:12,260 --> 00:02:14,502
like Eidos, EA, and eventually I entered LEGO.

33
00:02:15,962 --> 00:02:19,704
I was exposed to the family game market for the first time, and it was a really wonderful

34
00:02:19,744 --> 00:02:22,246
time, really on board a really, really wonderful family.

35
00:02:24,361 --> 00:02:26,262
And five years later, I entered London studio,

36
00:02:26,542 --> 00:02:28,923
still at Sony Computer Entertainment.

37
00:02:29,243 --> 00:02:31,084
And I was expecting to find a really kind of

38
00:02:31,144 --> 00:02:32,285
cold, hard tech company.

39
00:02:32,505 --> 00:02:33,505
Of course, it was PlayStation,

40
00:02:33,525 --> 00:02:35,766
but I expected to find a lot of kind of techie guys.

41
00:02:35,826 --> 00:02:38,007
But in the end, I was surprised to find a studio

42
00:02:38,027 --> 00:02:39,128
focused on the family market,

43
00:02:39,168 --> 00:02:40,608
with games like Sync Star, Eye Toy.

44
00:02:41,129 --> 00:02:43,190
And so I joined the studio as a producer

45
00:02:43,210 --> 00:02:44,110
on the Eye Toy franchise.

46
00:02:45,270 --> 00:02:46,571
And during the PS3 era,

47
00:02:46,691 --> 00:02:48,052
I worked on an augmented reality game.

48
00:02:48,412 --> 00:02:50,313
And that was my first time as a creative director.

49
00:02:51,133 --> 00:02:51,913
And then I made a big move.

50
00:02:53,165 --> 00:02:56,968
In 2011, I said goodbye to fish and chips and hello to sushi,

51
00:02:57,249 --> 00:02:58,310
and I moved to Japan Studio.

52
00:02:59,070 --> 00:03:02,093
It was like a kid's dream, really, for somebody like me

53
00:03:02,133 --> 00:03:05,096
who grew up playing video games from Japan.

54
00:03:06,780 --> 00:03:08,580
In 2012, Asobi Team was formed.

55
00:03:08,781 --> 00:03:13,282
So the team mission was to research gameplay

56
00:03:13,302 --> 00:03:14,583
using the new PlayStation hardware.

57
00:03:15,123 --> 00:03:18,164
And by the way, the name Asobi in Japan means to play.

58
00:03:19,265 --> 00:03:22,526
And we picked it because it should be a reminder that we

59
00:03:22,566 --> 00:03:23,967
should all be about play.

60
00:03:24,007 --> 00:03:25,868
And it's something I borrowed from LEGO, actually, which is

61
00:03:25,928 --> 00:03:30,610
also part of how the name LEGO came to be.

62
00:03:31,772 --> 00:03:36,257
And this is a world exclusive, it's a sneak peak, well it's not a sneak peak, an old peak

63
00:03:36,437 --> 00:03:39,882
at some of the iteration of the DualShock 4 controllers that we got to work with.

64
00:03:40,983 --> 00:03:44,667
And using these controllers we will try to come up with gameplay prototypes that could

65
00:03:44,707 --> 00:03:47,451
showcase the new features and also share them with other developers.

66
00:03:49,788 --> 00:03:52,691
The way we work is that we organize our thinking around four creative pillars.

67
00:03:52,831 --> 00:03:55,093
They're magical, innovative, playful, and inclusive.

68
00:03:55,934 --> 00:03:58,416
And these pillars really define the DNA of the team.

69
00:03:58,496 --> 00:04:01,640
And even Astro Boat was created with these four key pillars in mind.

70
00:04:03,642 --> 00:04:06,846
Then we spend quite a bit of time brainstorming with the team

71
00:04:07,427 --> 00:04:08,849
how to use these new technologies.

72
00:04:09,489 --> 00:04:12,593
It's a relaxing time where everybody gets to get all their ideas out.

73
00:04:13,334 --> 00:04:15,857
And of course, we have game designers, but we like to think that actually

74
00:04:15,937 --> 00:04:18,461
there is a game designer in every one of the team members,

75
00:04:18,501 --> 00:04:21,324
whether they're programmers, artists, or audio producers.

76
00:04:23,086 --> 00:04:27,649
And then our ideas kind of all go on Post-it. It all begins on a Post-it to be honest.

77
00:04:28,210 --> 00:04:29,951
And these are all of our walls in the office.

78
00:04:30,832 --> 00:04:34,795
And the concept of Astrobot along with all the game mechanics started on Post-its like this.

79
00:04:37,260 --> 00:04:38,861
So once we select an idea, we turn it

80
00:04:38,881 --> 00:04:40,722
into a very, very basic design document.

81
00:04:40,762 --> 00:04:42,683
We don't do big design docs.

82
00:04:43,403 --> 00:04:45,344
And these are mostly visual with minimal text.

83
00:04:45,584 --> 00:04:46,965
And the reason for that is because we

84
00:04:47,005 --> 00:04:48,706
want to visualize the experience really quickly,

85
00:04:48,846 --> 00:04:50,787
but also because writing and reading in Japanese

86
00:04:50,807 --> 00:04:52,968
and in English for us is actually quite a big hurdle.

87
00:04:54,049 --> 00:04:56,710
So we prefer simple sketches and talking face to face.

88
00:04:56,910 --> 00:04:58,651
It's quite a fairly old school way of working.

89
00:04:58,691 --> 00:05:00,652
It's very much like an indie team.

90
00:05:00,772 --> 00:05:02,433
But we find that it works really well for us.

91
00:05:04,399 --> 00:05:06,540
So once we've decided on a prototype,

92
00:05:07,160 --> 00:05:08,961
to create a prototype would generally take two weeks

93
00:05:09,302 --> 00:05:10,102
for a core mechanics.

94
00:05:10,202 --> 00:05:12,143
So for example, a boss battle in Astro Bot

95
00:05:12,203 --> 00:05:14,185
would have been two weeks of this programmer.

96
00:05:15,105 --> 00:05:16,646
And so that makes the gameplay programmers

97
00:05:16,686 --> 00:05:19,428
really central pieces to our development

98
00:05:19,468 --> 00:05:21,409
because they are the beginning of everything, really.

99
00:05:22,010 --> 00:05:24,191
It is them who are going to give the gameplay

100
00:05:24,231 --> 00:05:25,732
that initial kind of burst.

101
00:05:26,813 --> 00:05:30,135
And so later I will show you lots of prototypes,

102
00:05:30,175 --> 00:05:31,296
of course, for this presentation.

103
00:05:32,701 --> 00:05:34,402
So going back to all the days as a team,

104
00:05:34,683 --> 00:05:38,186
after creating lots of tech demos, we kind of polished them.

105
00:05:38,306 --> 00:05:40,628
And the best ones were eventually

106
00:05:40,688 --> 00:05:42,949
put together inside the PS4, known as the Playroom.

107
00:05:43,310 --> 00:05:44,471
So perhaps you've known the Playroom.

108
00:05:45,852 --> 00:05:48,514
And it contributed to giving PS4 a warm, inclusive image

109
00:05:48,554 --> 00:05:48,894
at launch.

110
00:05:48,954 --> 00:05:50,616
But you needed a camera to play this game.

111
00:05:51,877 --> 00:05:53,418
It was a great training ground for the team as well,

112
00:05:54,179 --> 00:05:55,740
because many of the members actually never

113
00:05:55,820 --> 00:05:56,661
worked on a game before.

114
00:05:56,721 --> 00:05:57,702
It was their first time ever.

115
00:06:00,039 --> 00:06:02,460
In 2013, the VR headset project Morpheus came along,

116
00:06:02,840 --> 00:06:04,041
and so we jumped on the opportunity

117
00:06:04,081 --> 00:06:08,044
to reiterate with this kind of gameplay research.

118
00:06:08,784 --> 00:06:12,026
And we started researching new opportunities to play in VR.

119
00:06:14,047 --> 00:06:16,669
So once again, we created many demos, particularly

120
00:06:16,729 --> 00:06:17,770
around multiplayer.

121
00:06:17,830 --> 00:06:21,332
So we had this concept of being able to play in VR and on a TV.

122
00:06:23,561 --> 00:06:26,322
And I did a talk in GDC in 2015, I think, about this.

123
00:06:26,362 --> 00:06:28,083
So if you want to know more about these prototypes,

124
00:06:28,103 --> 00:06:29,263
you can look at that.

125
00:06:29,543 --> 00:06:31,744
And during that phase of trials,

126
00:06:32,724 --> 00:06:34,325
we also tried third-person platforming.

127
00:06:34,765 --> 00:06:36,305
And that was strange because it felt really like,

128
00:06:36,486 --> 00:06:38,426
it wasn't very much like a VR.

129
00:06:38,466 --> 00:06:40,847
VR should be a first-person, virtual hands.

130
00:06:41,347 --> 00:06:43,128
But we kind of wanted to try it, and we did.

131
00:06:43,588 --> 00:06:46,149
And we found it actually was pretty cool.

132
00:06:47,509 --> 00:06:48,650
And this is what it looked like.

133
00:06:48,950 --> 00:06:50,730
It's our first VR platformer prototype.

134
00:06:53,320 --> 00:06:55,801
So as you can see, some of Astro Bot's trademark,

135
00:06:56,262 --> 00:06:58,122
like jumping around, jumping from the controller,

136
00:06:58,323 --> 00:06:59,623
were already in there from the beginning.

137
00:07:00,383 --> 00:07:01,664
And the controls were very simple.

138
00:07:01,704 --> 00:07:02,865
You can move around and jump.

139
00:07:03,065 --> 00:07:04,685
There was no punching or enemies at the time.

140
00:07:07,447 --> 00:07:11,148
And then we included moving into Z, you know,

141
00:07:12,129 --> 00:07:12,749
so navigation.

142
00:07:13,950 --> 00:07:15,510
And finally, the character looking back at you,

143
00:07:15,550 --> 00:07:17,231
that was something that we did a quick test for

144
00:07:17,311 --> 00:07:19,892
and we thought that it gives a lot of charm

145
00:07:19,992 --> 00:07:21,093
to the experience.

146
00:07:22,743 --> 00:07:24,785
And then eventually it became Robot Rescue.

147
00:07:25,185 --> 00:07:29,970
And Robot Rescue was included as part of the Playroom VR.

148
00:07:29,990 --> 00:07:31,131
And it was a single stage.

149
00:07:32,592 --> 00:07:33,713
It figured a character.

150
00:07:33,733 --> 00:07:35,374
At the time, there was no Astro Bot.

151
00:07:35,955 --> 00:07:37,376
But the core mechanics were there.

152
00:07:37,416 --> 00:07:38,497
You could rescue little robots.

153
00:07:38,537 --> 00:07:40,759
There was one gadget, which was the hook shot.

154
00:07:41,560 --> 00:07:43,722
Some verticality, some vertical gameplay.

155
00:07:45,518 --> 00:07:46,959
And the whole game lasted about 15 minutes,

156
00:07:47,479 --> 00:07:49,600
and it was created by half a dozen people

157
00:07:49,861 --> 00:07:50,701
in three to four months.

158
00:07:50,881 --> 00:07:52,642
It was part of a bigger game collection.

159
00:07:53,883 --> 00:07:55,464
And the bigger collection, it was called the Playroom VR,

160
00:07:55,504 --> 00:07:57,566
and it was mostly a big party game.

161
00:07:58,771 --> 00:08:02,474
And as a result, Robot Rescue was kind of the old one out,

162
00:08:02,494 --> 00:08:02,695
really.

163
00:08:02,955 --> 00:08:04,256
But we put it in because we really,

164
00:08:04,636 --> 00:08:06,498
if we didn't put it in at that time,

165
00:08:06,518 --> 00:08:07,479
it would have just gone to waste.

166
00:08:07,539 --> 00:08:08,800
It would have gone lost.

167
00:08:09,361 --> 00:08:12,564
So we wanted to make sure that we would still use it.

168
00:08:12,844 --> 00:08:14,185
And so it was the old one out.

169
00:08:14,766 --> 00:08:16,667
And it was put into the Playroom VR.

170
00:08:18,889 --> 00:08:19,470
And that was the end.

171
00:08:20,110 --> 00:08:20,451
And that's it.

172
00:08:20,571 --> 00:08:21,892
And I remember that was like Christmas 2016.

173
00:08:24,680 --> 00:08:28,522
and around that time, the holiday time, and I was in bed and I was thinking,

174
00:08:28,962 --> 00:08:32,505
right, next year we're going to have to start a new project and, you know, the team should be busy

175
00:08:32,545 --> 00:08:35,446
from the beginning. What are we going to do? You know, are we going to do like a bigger party game?

176
00:08:36,367 --> 00:08:40,009
And really inside of myself and I think the team as well, we really wanted to make a big platformer,

177
00:08:40,069 --> 00:08:45,452
but it really felt like it's not a true VR game. And there's a bit of a trauma there, I think,

178
00:08:45,472 --> 00:08:48,734
because, you know, we've heard so many times that it should be first person and virtual hands that,

179
00:08:48,754 --> 00:08:49,515
you know, it felt like a...

180
00:08:51,294 --> 00:08:53,236
And we kind of, you know, I slept on it.

181
00:08:53,757 --> 00:08:56,139
And eventually the answer actually came from the community.

182
00:08:57,875 --> 00:09:00,616
So looking back on the net for reviews of Playroom VR,

183
00:09:00,656 --> 00:09:03,077
we came across a lot of requests, actually, from gamers.

184
00:09:04,918 --> 00:09:06,859
Playroom VR kind of worked with dad and the kids

185
00:09:06,919 --> 00:09:07,819
and playing as a family.

186
00:09:07,859 --> 00:09:10,360
But the gamers, actually, they really

187
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:14,062
resonated with Robo Rescue.

188
00:09:14,102 --> 00:09:15,162
And they wanted a bigger game.

189
00:09:15,743 --> 00:09:16,903
So that was the last push we needed.

190
00:09:17,063 --> 00:09:17,963
And then came New Year.

191
00:09:18,364 --> 00:09:22,325
We began working on the cleverly named Super Robo Rescue.

192
00:09:23,927 --> 00:09:26,352
So that was an internal name to just make it clear to everyone.

193
00:09:26,372 --> 00:09:28,937
Yeah, we're making the big version, right?

194
00:09:30,059 --> 00:09:32,204
But actually, that name stayed on for very, very, very long.

195
00:09:32,805 --> 00:09:33,767
Scarily long, in fact.

196
00:09:35,296 --> 00:09:37,037
So, Robo Rescue was really cool and fun,

197
00:09:37,238 --> 00:09:38,759
but we needed a bigger game,

198
00:09:38,799 --> 00:09:40,440
and we couldn't afford to just copy and paste

199
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:42,241
those 15 minutes and stretch them.

200
00:09:43,963 --> 00:09:45,684
So we needed variety and lots of it.

201
00:09:45,764 --> 00:09:48,206
So we're finally hitting the meat of today's talk, really.

202
00:09:48,967 --> 00:09:50,728
So today I'm gonna take you through 10 topics

203
00:09:50,888 --> 00:09:52,870
that we focused on to make Astro Bot what it is.

204
00:09:53,810 --> 00:09:55,071
And of course, that's not everything.

205
00:09:56,352 --> 00:09:58,214
But I think it encompasses some of the most

206
00:09:58,334 --> 00:10:00,976
important elements of the game design.

207
00:10:00,996 --> 00:10:02,637
All right, so let's go.

208
00:10:04,275 --> 00:10:06,995
So I'm a kind of retro game fan, and if you know games

209
00:10:07,015 --> 00:10:09,236
like Castlevania or Grues and Ghosts, you know the map,

210
00:10:09,336 --> 00:10:09,936
you know the quest.

211
00:10:10,717 --> 00:10:13,217
So only we're not saving a princess, we're making a game.

212
00:10:13,257 --> 00:10:15,358
So it starts with VRness.

213
00:10:16,638 --> 00:10:24,140
So VRness, OK, it's probably the number one feature of the

214
00:10:24,180 --> 00:10:26,881
game design, in fact, that differentiate this game from

215
00:10:27,982 --> 00:10:29,522
traditional TV games.

216
00:10:30,767 --> 00:10:33,572
So early on, we established that to realize the full potential

217
00:10:33,592 --> 00:10:37,258
of VR, you have to become the only way to operate

218
00:10:37,278 --> 00:10:37,919
the camera in a game.

219
00:10:39,141 --> 00:10:41,525
And so we decided to continue not using the right stick

220
00:10:42,947 --> 00:10:45,711
and instead look for fun ways for you to use your body.

221
00:10:48,682 --> 00:10:50,123
And that became the VRness.

222
00:10:50,143 --> 00:10:51,803
So behind that barbaric use of English,

223
00:10:51,863 --> 00:10:53,944
it's an ensemble of gameplay mechanics

224
00:10:53,964 --> 00:10:54,904
that take advantage of VR.

225
00:10:54,924 --> 00:10:57,865
So for example, perspective play that lets you see

226
00:10:57,885 --> 00:10:58,545
behind an object.

227
00:10:59,345 --> 00:11:03,647
Vertical play with big drops and gameplay

228
00:11:03,667 --> 00:11:06,568
that kind of forces you to look up and down in a way.

229
00:11:08,368 --> 00:11:09,008
360 play all around you.

230
00:11:09,048 --> 00:11:10,209
And then near and far play, which

231
00:11:10,309 --> 00:11:11,929
is playing with distances between you

232
00:11:11,949 --> 00:11:12,669
and your main character.

233
00:11:13,170 --> 00:11:15,190
So we're going to go through each one of those in detail now.

234
00:11:16,148 --> 00:11:18,210
So perspective play, so this is about leaning with your body

235
00:11:18,730 --> 00:11:20,010
to see behind a wall, for example,

236
00:11:20,030 --> 00:11:22,092
and that complements platforming really, really well.

237
00:11:22,252 --> 00:11:24,733
It works really well as a set with jumping around.

238
00:11:25,633 --> 00:11:27,554
And so we've been using this at every opportunity

239
00:11:28,355 --> 00:11:29,095
in every level.

240
00:11:31,136 --> 00:11:32,277
So here you can see you're leaning,

241
00:11:32,557 --> 00:11:34,098
you see some coins, that's a guide.

242
00:11:34,618 --> 00:11:35,659
And then you can use it as a way

243
00:11:35,679 --> 00:11:36,799
to surprise the user as well.

244
00:11:36,859 --> 00:11:38,260
So we thought like here, you're leaning,

245
00:11:38,280 --> 00:11:40,281
you're not seeing anything, and then the moment you lean,

246
00:11:40,301 --> 00:11:42,342
you can see two enemies and you have to take them out.

247
00:11:43,334 --> 00:11:47,279
And these enemies actually, they come up from behind the wall, and that's a really useful way to create a hint.

248
00:11:47,399 --> 00:11:50,563
Because once these enemies come from behind the wall, the next thing you want to do is like,

249
00:11:50,663 --> 00:11:52,245
