735
00:34:37,511 --> 00:34:39,451
So this is something that exists in every game

736
00:34:39,511 --> 00:34:40,592
or should exist in every game,

737
00:34:40,772 --> 00:34:42,772
but I think in VR, it's that much more important,

738
00:34:43,432 --> 00:34:46,113
and that's having a world that is completely, like, reactive.

739
00:34:46,233 --> 00:34:49,254
So everything reacts to you and Astro's presence.

740
00:34:50,074 --> 00:34:53,195
So every object in the game, we added some dynamic properties

741
00:34:53,255 --> 00:34:56,195
so that you could punch them, and they would react.

742
00:34:56,235 --> 00:34:58,156
Even platforms would kind of, you know, bob slightly

743
00:34:58,216 --> 00:34:58,856
when you jump on them.

744
00:34:59,878 --> 00:35:04,387
And sometimes we link that to a more kind of like full screen or kind of large scale effect.

745
00:35:04,407 --> 00:35:06,110
So Astro here is triggering some fireflies.

746
00:35:06,531 --> 00:35:08,175
And that's for your benefit as a VR player.

747
00:35:08,235 --> 00:35:10,680
It's all around you and you get that kind of, you know, moment.

748
00:35:12,747 --> 00:35:14,028
This is for you, my friends.

749
00:35:14,348 --> 00:35:15,869
A little heart.

750
00:35:16,730 --> 00:35:17,570
Right.

751
00:35:17,911 --> 00:35:18,791
The same thing with the gadgets.

752
00:35:18,891 --> 00:35:21,794
So we have the same philosophy, where the gadgets should be toys.

753
00:35:22,634 --> 00:35:24,696
So beside their functional use,

754
00:35:25,616 --> 00:35:27,418
for example, like you shoot enemies, they react.

755
00:35:27,458 --> 00:35:29,699
If you shoot an electric enemy, you electrify yourself.

756
00:35:30,620 --> 00:35:32,742
Even the guys you rescue, you can be mean to them.

757
00:35:33,342 --> 00:35:35,684
And even Astro. Here, you're on an elevator going to the boss,

758
00:35:35,724 --> 00:35:38,126
and you can just, you know, be mean to Astro.

759
00:35:40,224 --> 00:35:45,558
You can also beam into yourself, you can splash yourself in the face, and you can even shuriken your own face.

760
00:35:48,040 --> 00:35:49,940
Yeah, and you break the headset.

761
00:35:49,980 --> 00:35:50,900
So it's kind of funny.

762
00:35:51,621 --> 00:35:53,341
Yeah, this is stuff we did at the end of a project.

763
00:35:53,361 --> 00:35:55,142
We really reserved some time to really do

764
00:35:55,262 --> 00:35:56,142
all of these little things,

765
00:35:56,202 --> 00:35:58,382
because they're the ones that come out in the review,

766
00:35:58,482 --> 00:35:59,283
actually, in the reviews.

767
00:35:59,363 --> 00:36:00,983
People go, oh, I tried that, and I tried that,

768
00:36:01,483 --> 00:36:02,804
and it did this and that, so yeah.

769
00:36:03,904 --> 00:36:06,605
Equally, the bosses have like a fun finished treatment,

770
00:36:07,065 --> 00:36:09,065
and it's usually tied to gadgets and VRness.

771
00:36:09,165 --> 00:36:10,446
So for example, here you have the octopus.

772
00:36:10,606 --> 00:36:12,066
You fill up the octopus with water.

773
00:36:13,166 --> 00:36:13,987
He gets really, really big,

774
00:36:14,007 --> 00:36:15,547
and at the end you get a verticality moment.

775
00:36:16,287 --> 00:36:18,410
Yeah, yeah.

776
00:36:18,470 --> 00:36:20,253
That's the spider, so you finish off the spider,

777
00:36:20,293 --> 00:36:23,517
and then you have to use the gadget to crack a corset open.

778
00:36:26,261 --> 00:36:26,421
Yeah.

779
00:36:28,624 --> 00:36:30,387
And if you look away as you're doing it,

780
00:36:30,447 --> 00:36:31,929
you get a trophy for being a gentleman.

781
00:36:36,413 --> 00:36:39,035
Right, so that's the kind of playfulness and humor side.

782
00:36:39,555 --> 00:36:41,756
Next, this is about platforming fundamentals.

783
00:36:41,776 --> 00:36:43,978
So we are making a VR game with lots of VRness

784
00:36:44,158 --> 00:36:45,659
and lots of VR tricks, but really,

785
00:36:46,279 --> 00:36:49,561
like every good platformer, we need some really solid controls.

786
00:36:50,281 --> 00:36:52,363
And that's an area that we worked on from Robo Rescue,

787
00:36:52,383 --> 00:36:54,804
and we kept refining it throughout Astro Bot.

788
00:36:54,844 --> 00:36:57,026
So the character weight, inertia, acceleration,

789
00:36:58,046 --> 00:36:59,727
the way every action can be chained together,

790
00:37:00,368 --> 00:37:02,089
the way the animations and the inputs

791
00:37:02,129 --> 00:37:03,590
are kind of like, you know, so blending.

792
00:37:04,930 --> 00:37:08,993
All of these states work together in harmony, and that was really important

793
00:37:10,774 --> 00:37:14,196
to create a smooth game. So even if you were to play it on the TV, you should feel the same way.

794
00:37:16,502 --> 00:37:19,083
But we've had to adapt the controls a little bit.

795
00:37:19,424 --> 00:37:20,905
We've had to refine them.

796
00:37:21,125 --> 00:37:22,226
So for example, here, if you look,

797
00:37:22,246 --> 00:37:25,728
I'm pushing up on the left stick continuously.

798
00:37:25,908 --> 00:37:27,789
But I'm looking left and right as I'm running along.

799
00:37:28,330 --> 00:37:30,211
And so Astro is adjusting his course, actually,

800
00:37:31,412 --> 00:37:32,292
according to where I'm looking.

801
00:37:32,833 --> 00:37:34,914
So of course, a lot of games do that also with the right stick.

802
00:37:34,974 --> 00:37:39,537
But here, we're talking about really very, very

803
00:37:39,597 --> 00:37:40,578
brutal camera movement.

804
00:37:40,598 --> 00:37:42,760
For example, here in this section, I'm going to go down.

805
00:37:44,329 --> 00:37:46,811
So all the controls are now mapped to be, you know, from that point of view.

806
00:37:46,831 --> 00:37:50,695
Then I go up and then the controls are kind of remapped in real time.

807
00:37:50,715 --> 00:37:53,278
So it's like we've had to spend quite a lot of time actually.

808
00:37:56,316 --> 00:37:59,477
getting rid of all the cases where you felt like you're trying to go in a straight line

809
00:37:59,517 --> 00:38:06,959
and basically you'd go in a zig-zag, because your angle of view would be a little bit strange.

810
00:38:07,399 --> 00:38:10,220
And so in the end, you're able to control Astro even looking away.

811
00:38:11,300 --> 00:38:14,781
So that took quite some time to implement.

812
00:38:16,322 --> 00:38:20,925
But a big one, actually, is about being able to judge your 3D position.

813
00:38:22,006 --> 00:38:27,850
And so we use these lasers under Astro's boots to actually give you an extra hint of where

814
00:38:27,970 --> 00:38:29,131
you are in relation to the ground.

815
00:38:29,911 --> 00:38:34,375
And this is, this became really, really, really useful, especially in low visibility.

816
00:38:34,395 --> 00:38:38,237
So for example, here you're playing from underneath, and all you have is a shadow, but having the

817
00:38:38,257 --> 00:38:41,120
lasers to really judge where you're going to land on each platform.

818
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:44,983
Plus the fact it's hovering, so you have an extra time actually during those sections.

819
00:38:45,624 --> 00:38:46,564
That's really, really useful.

820
00:38:48,226 --> 00:38:53,070
Another thing we did, something that many traditional games do, but it was the first

821
00:38:53,270 --> 00:38:54,752
for us, it was about the teetering.

822
00:38:54,832 --> 00:38:57,234
So when a location is safe to drop from.

823
00:38:58,471 --> 00:38:59,272
you can just drop down.

824
00:38:59,432 --> 00:39:01,013
But when a location is unsafe

825
00:39:01,434 --> 00:39:03,255
or is going to have a big-time penalty,

826
00:39:03,616 --> 00:39:04,597
we've added a teetering,

827
00:39:05,257 --> 00:39:06,358
and this is something the game designers

828
00:39:06,378 --> 00:39:08,580
can just add to a ledge.

829
00:39:09,161 --> 00:39:10,742
And you can override the teetering by jumping.

830
00:39:12,043 --> 00:39:14,245
Without it, the game is really frustrating to play.

831
00:39:14,666 --> 00:39:15,407
You fall down a lot.

832
00:39:16,267 --> 00:39:17,368
So depending on the situation,

833
00:39:17,989 --> 00:39:19,610
we added this teetering.

834
00:39:20,011 --> 00:39:21,152
And of course, everything else

835
00:39:21,612 --> 00:39:22,613
that has to go in the real game,

836
00:39:22,793 --> 00:39:23,734
I really hate that term,

837
00:39:23,774 --> 00:39:24,775
but it's like, you know, that...

838
00:39:25,175 --> 00:39:27,998
he felt working on a VR game, you know, let's be a real game.

839
00:39:28,518 --> 00:39:33,782
So enemies, pickups, collectibles, a progression system based on collectibles,

840
00:39:34,763 --> 00:39:38,105
challenge so that, you know, the very, very skillful players have something like to get

841
00:39:38,125 --> 00:39:41,628
their teeth into, a collection room, and of course, soundtrack, you know,

842
00:39:41,648 --> 00:39:42,689
that goes with a good action game.

843
00:39:44,799 --> 00:39:47,741
That's from Kenny Young, who is not here anymore.

844
00:39:47,841 --> 00:39:48,521
But, yeah.

845
00:39:49,122 --> 00:39:49,262
Um...

846
00:39:50,562 --> 00:39:51,183
No, he's still alive.

847
00:39:51,243 --> 00:39:52,063
He's just left the room.

848
00:39:52,243 --> 00:39:53,224
He was there at the beginning.

849
00:39:53,244 --> 00:39:53,444
He's...

850
00:39:54,024 --> 00:39:54,364
So...

851
00:39:56,366 --> 00:39:56,546
Yes.

852
00:39:57,866 --> 00:39:58,006
Um...

853
00:39:58,607 --> 00:39:58,947
Comfort.

854
00:39:59,087 --> 00:40:01,228
So that's really important for VR games.

855
00:40:01,869 --> 00:40:04,830
Actually, in Astro Bot, the levels are perfectly straight.

856
00:40:05,391 --> 00:40:08,612
So the start point and the end point are perfectly aligned.

857
00:40:08,752 --> 00:40:09,573
You go in a straight line.

858
00:40:10,093 --> 00:40:10,173
Choo!

859
00:40:11,034 --> 00:40:13,516
But it's actually astral that goes left, right, up, and down.

860
00:40:13,736 --> 00:40:16,158
So the levels are built to be twisting around you.

861
00:40:16,378 --> 00:40:18,200
And at the end of the level, if you ask somebody,

862
00:40:18,220 --> 00:40:20,202
how did you feel that you went, they

863
00:40:20,222 --> 00:40:22,284
will tell you I've gone up and down and left and right.

864
00:40:22,324 --> 00:40:24,826
But in fact, your body has gone in a straight line.

865
00:40:26,247 --> 00:40:28,048
Apart from vertical level, but even vertical level

866
00:40:28,068 --> 00:40:29,570
go in a straight line, but just upwards.

867
00:40:30,691 --> 00:40:34,154
And so that was really important to agree on this

868
00:40:34,394 --> 00:40:35,535
and to stick to it.

869
00:40:37,196 --> 00:40:38,377
Also, there is an invisible leash.

870
00:40:40,213 --> 00:40:42,254
This is how we kind of go around doing traversal.

871
00:40:42,575 --> 00:40:43,955
That was back in Robot Rescue as well.

872
00:40:43,975 --> 00:40:46,416
So there is an invisible line, if you like,

873
00:40:46,456 --> 00:40:47,637
and it's slightly curved outwards.

874
00:40:48,197 --> 00:40:50,498
And if Astro crosses that line, you move with him.

875
00:40:52,619 --> 00:40:54,360
It feels strange at first, because you

876
00:40:54,500 --> 00:40:55,800
have no reference point.

877
00:40:56,341 --> 00:40:57,901
But over time, in your brain, you

878
00:40:57,921 --> 00:41:00,783
get this print of exactly where that invisible line is.

879
00:41:01,363 --> 00:41:03,024
And when you start moving, you know that you're moving.

880
00:41:03,084 --> 00:41:05,525
And so therefore, you become in control of the movement.

881
00:41:05,565 --> 00:41:07,606
And therefore, the sickness really kind of seems to go away.

882
00:41:08,326 --> 00:41:13,908
Now the important part is to really be consistent, and so that distance and that speed were never changed.

883
00:41:14,448 --> 00:41:15,648
We were not allowed to change the speed.

884
00:41:15,688 --> 00:41:20,950
So, it's 1.1 meters away from you in terms of distance, and 1 meter per second in terms of speed.

885
00:41:20,970 --> 00:41:24,071
And the 1 meter per second, so I've been talking to the gameplay programmer,

886
00:41:24,571 --> 00:41:28,632
it's not a random thing that he just decided like that, actually, we went back and forth quite a lot.

887
00:41:28,772 --> 00:41:31,633
And in the end it ended up being 1 meter per second, so it's easy to remember.

888
00:41:33,014 --> 00:41:33,614
But, yeah.

889
00:41:34,474 --> 00:41:37,755
And that distance, because it's always the same, you know when you're going to be moving.

890
00:41:40,170 --> 00:41:42,591
There is one time where we break that rule,

891
00:41:43,051 --> 00:41:44,792
and we have something called a stopper.

892
00:41:45,172 --> 00:41:47,413
So sometimes we don't want to follow Astro,

893
00:41:47,513 --> 00:41:51,274
we want to have some gap between Astro and the player,

894
00:41:51,734 --> 00:41:54,255
so that you have a big space to play inside of.

895
00:41:55,515 --> 00:41:57,716
So we've developed a system which is called a stopper.

896
00:41:57,856 --> 00:41:58,516
It's very simple.

897
00:41:58,676 --> 00:41:59,937
You enter a zone which is a stop,

898
00:41:59,997 --> 00:42:01,737
and there is a zone which is a kind of unlock.

899
00:42:02,078 --> 00:42:02,858
This goes on.

900
00:42:02,958 --> 00:42:05,819
So for as long as you're inside that zone,

901
00:42:05,839 --> 00:42:06,599
you're not moving forward.

902
00:42:08,973 --> 00:42:12,100
And as soon as Astro passes that trigger point.

903
00:42:13,535 --> 00:42:14,476
then you move together again.

904
00:42:15,697 --> 00:42:17,198
Now the trick is to put that trigger point

905
00:42:17,678 --> 00:42:19,780
within the 1.1 meter that we talked about earlier,

906
00:42:19,880 --> 00:42:21,361
so that when you move together again,

907
00:42:21,401 --> 00:42:23,662
there isn't a need for catching up quickly

908
00:42:23,702 --> 00:42:24,983
and making you feel sick.

909
00:42:26,584 --> 00:42:27,885
It's a simple thing, but actually it means

910
00:42:27,925 --> 00:42:30,026
that you can create a big space,

911
00:42:30,086 --> 00:42:31,307
and especially when you have gadget play

912
00:42:31,347 --> 00:42:34,469
and you want a lot of space for shooting, for example,

913
00:42:35,450 --> 00:42:37,251
you have a stopper, Astro is far away from you,

914
00:42:37,291 --> 00:42:38,152
you're kind of shooting around,

915
00:42:38,232 --> 00:42:39,653
and then you make Astro come back close to you

916
00:42:39,713 --> 00:42:40,513
and you move together again.

917
00:42:44,794 --> 00:42:46,035
Next is the no going back.

918
00:42:46,075 --> 00:42:47,615
So this is something we had in Robo Rescue

919
00:42:47,655 --> 00:42:48,776
and we removed from AstroBot.

920
00:42:48,896 --> 00:42:50,817
We found that people were feeling sick

921
00:42:51,037 --> 00:42:51,957
when going backwards.

922
00:42:53,137 --> 00:42:54,578
And so we made it impossible to go backwards.

923
00:42:55,358 --> 00:42:56,939
Astro can go backwards, obviously.

924
00:42:58,392 --> 00:43:01,934
And so Astro is able to go back all the way to the beginning of the level and he gets really, really, really tiny.

925
00:43:02,574 --> 00:43:03,134
But you don't move.

926
00:43:04,195 --> 00:43:08,196
And in the end, it's really not the best solution, but what we thought is that

927
00:43:09,137 --> 00:43:12,218
we just created levels that minimized the motivation for going backwards.

928
00:43:12,798 --> 00:43:14,879
So as much as possible, we make it so that, you know,

929
00:43:15,299 --> 00:43:18,100
we could have made the level destroyed behind you, but that would have been a little bit sad.

930
00:43:18,120 --> 00:43:20,661
You know, every time you look around, it's just like, nothing.

931
00:43:21,262 --> 00:43:23,263
So in the end, we just went for this.

932
00:43:24,963 --> 00:43:26,984
And yeah, it's not perfect, but it works.

933
00:43:29,490 --> 00:43:31,130
Okay, so the controller often gets in the way,

934
00:43:31,390 --> 00:43:33,771
and that's something that happens in games

935
00:43:34,512 --> 00:43:35,312
with camera and walls,

936
00:43:35,732 --> 00:43:37,333
but basically we used a lot of transparency

937
00:43:37,613 --> 00:43:39,073
whenever Astro was behind the controller

938
00:43:39,313 --> 00:43:40,214
or under your body.

939
00:43:42,194 --> 00:43:44,055
And that was really useful for vertical gameplay

940
00:43:44,075 --> 00:43:45,595
because sometimes you need to see,

941
00:43:46,196 --> 00:43:47,816
yeah, Astro just under you.

942
00:43:49,197 --> 00:43:50,557
And so during those times, yeah.

943
00:43:52,338 --> 00:43:54,119
That was really useful to have that transparency.

944
00:43:54,139 --> 00:43:55,599
It's a classic thing in games,

945
00:43:55,659 --> 00:43:58,900
but it was a first for us as well.

946
00:44:01,060 --> 00:44:03,541
The respawn, to deal with death and respawn transition,

947
00:44:03,881 --> 00:44:05,722
we went with very simple, quick fade to black.

948
00:44:05,782 --> 00:44:07,423
So you will see here, oops.

949
00:44:08,424 --> 00:44:13,046
Okay, I've got, sorry, I should have told you,

950
00:44:13,106 --> 00:44:19,069
but once per presentation, I crash, so there you go.

951
00:44:19,129 --> 00:44:19,450
Once again.

952
00:44:21,860 --> 00:44:23,521
So this is the respawn fade.

953
00:44:23,581 --> 00:44:26,463
So you're gonna see here, gonna die, okay.

954
00:44:26,803 --> 00:44:27,904
And this is a quick black screen.

955
00:44:28,725 --> 00:44:31,166
So we tried lots of kind of really intricate effects

956
00:44:31,206 --> 00:44:32,387
with the screen shattering

957
00:44:32,427 --> 00:44:34,348
and then some kind of respawning in first person,

958
00:44:34,368 --> 00:44:36,009
but especially when you have something like that,

959
00:44:36,049 --> 00:44:37,830
like the Minecraft level where you're going at high speed.

960
00:44:38,410 --> 00:44:39,531
The last thing you want to do at that point

961
00:44:39,591 --> 00:44:41,712
is to bring lots of effects and things like that.

962
00:44:41,733 --> 00:44:45,335
So we did that and it didn't do anything good really.

963
00:44:45,395 --> 00:44:46,816
It just made people more uncomfortable.

964
00:44:46,916 --> 00:44:48,457
So we just went for fade to black.

965
00:44:50,855 --> 00:44:52,816
Okay, two more sections.

966
00:44:53,076 --> 00:44:54,137
First one is level building.

967
00:44:57,158 --> 00:45:00,900
So this is about how we got around to editing our levels.

968
00:45:01,200 --> 00:45:02,261
So this is our level editor.

969
00:45:02,281 --> 00:45:04,142
It's in Maya, and it's hooked up to the game in real time.

970
00:45:04,562 --> 00:45:07,203
And alone, it still means that you have to put the headset on regularly,

971
00:45:07,243 --> 00:45:09,024
but the great thing about it is that it's real time.

972
00:45:10,757 --> 00:45:11,937
So when you make a change in Maya,

973
00:45:12,237 --> 00:45:15,639
it's reflected in the game within a fraction of a second.

974
00:45:16,099 --> 00:45:17,600
And it's really good for working as a pair.

975
00:45:18,200 --> 00:45:19,541
So one person is controlling Maya,

976
00:45:19,621 --> 00:45:22,802
one person is in VR just giving feedback and orders.

977
00:45:23,483 --> 00:45:25,583
And then, yeah, you can build a level together

978
00:45:25,684 --> 00:45:26,284
like that with a friend.

979
00:45:29,625 --> 00:45:30,906
We didn't always do that, of course,

980
00:45:30,946 --> 00:45:33,207
because it means having two people working together.

981
00:45:34,748 --> 00:45:37,189
But here, for example, stretching up, that's done.

982
00:45:38,590 --> 00:45:38,730
Yay.

983
00:45:41,263 --> 00:45:42,564
They say hello to all of you, by the way.

984
00:45:43,905 --> 00:45:46,127
OK, also we made the levels from building blocks.

985
00:45:46,207 --> 00:45:48,969
So these are really basic shapes that the designers can use.

986
00:45:49,590 --> 00:45:51,952
And they can change the scales to some extent,

987
00:45:51,992 --> 00:45:53,593
but they can't really mess around with them too much,

988
00:45:53,873 --> 00:45:56,335
because the idea is to keep the base proportions.

989
00:45:57,594 --> 00:46:00,316
So the artist then come in and replace those blocks

990
00:46:00,857 --> 00:46:04,080
with art versions and then add topicals and things like that.

991
00:46:04,380 --> 00:46:05,641
And of course, there are special pieces,

992
00:46:05,781 --> 00:46:07,422
which are special props, and these ones

993
00:46:07,502 --> 00:46:08,883
are kind of custom made.

994
00:46:09,944 --> 00:46:12,026
But in general, for the large majority

995
00:46:12,066 --> 00:46:14,468
of the base of the level, we're using this system.

996
00:46:14,548 --> 00:46:16,810
And we only did the principle,

997
00:46:17,931 --> 00:46:19,312
we only really used that properly

998
00:46:19,372 --> 00:46:20,253
near the end of a project.

999
00:46:20,313 --> 00:46:21,794
It took us some time to really kind of

1000
00:46:22,415 --> 00:46:25,017
break some old habits, but now we're kind of

1001
00:46:25,097 --> 00:46:26,858
in a mindset of working with building blocks.

1002
00:46:27,990 --> 00:46:30,392
And also it means that sections of levels can be repurposed.

1003
00:46:30,412 --> 00:46:31,993
So for example, here we had a canyon level,

1004
00:46:32,013 --> 00:46:34,695
but it was too long, just too long.

1005
00:46:34,775 --> 00:46:38,677
So we chopped up the last part, and we brought it

1006
00:46:38,837 --> 00:46:40,578
to the fire stage.

1007
00:46:40,979 --> 00:46:42,440
And we kind of repurposed the assets,

1008
00:46:42,760 --> 00:46:44,861
or kind of changed the textures, et cetera.

1009
00:46:45,562 --> 00:46:47,543
And that was the first section of another level.

1010
00:46:47,563 --> 00:46:50,385
So it was a really efficient way of working and kind

1011
00:46:50,425 --> 00:46:51,345
of shifting stuff around.

1012
00:46:51,385 --> 00:46:52,886
And near the end of the project, we

1013
00:46:52,906 --> 00:46:55,368
were really still shifting big parts of level.

1014
00:46:56,289 --> 00:46:58,229
Now, to achieve variety, we had a checklist

1015
00:46:58,950 --> 00:47:00,331
of how the levels were distributed.

1016
00:47:00,371 --> 00:47:02,071
And also, we updated that checklist

1017
00:47:02,492 --> 00:47:04,593
with all of the sections I've been talking about today,

1018
00:47:04,653 --> 00:47:07,454
VRness, physical play, gadgets, stuff like that.

1019
00:47:07,514 --> 00:47:09,095
And then we just populated.

1020
00:47:11,156 --> 00:47:14,397
And the idea wasn't to just fill the entire table,

1021
00:47:14,457 --> 00:47:16,338
because that would have been overstimulating for the player.

1022
00:47:16,478 --> 00:47:19,100
But the idea is to just get a good idea of whether we kind

1023
00:47:19,160 --> 00:47:21,181
of balanced as an experience.

1024
00:47:23,573 --> 00:47:24,735
And then the last thing is gameplay first.

1025
00:47:24,755 --> 00:47:26,616
So going back to the beginning of the presentation,

1026
00:47:26,636 --> 00:47:28,098
you know, we prototype a lot,

1027
00:47:28,298 --> 00:47:30,800
and that means actually every single piece of gameplay,

1028
00:47:30,860 --> 00:47:33,122
we always do it first with a gameplay programmer on his own,

1029
00:47:33,763 --> 00:47:34,764
and then we bring the artist.

1030
00:47:34,824 --> 00:47:36,425
And we never break that rule,

1031
00:47:36,465 --> 00:47:38,767
and when we break that rule, it's always a mess.

1032
00:47:38,987 --> 00:47:41,970
We end up with just like, you know, in difficult situations.

1033
00:47:42,010 --> 00:47:43,511
So here's the Dandelion.

1034
00:47:43,531 --> 00:47:44,993
That's the programmer's version, art version,

1035
00:47:45,033 --> 00:47:46,414
programmer version, art version.

1036
00:47:53,139 --> 00:47:55,411
So that's the water gadget first prototype.

1037
00:47:59,740 --> 00:48:02,000
And that's also true of transitions,

1038
00:48:02,100 --> 00:48:04,061
like this is a game designer's whale,

1039
00:48:04,561 --> 00:48:05,501
and then the big whale.

1040
00:48:06,081 --> 00:48:09,122
That's the boss from the Gorilla Boss.

1041
00:48:09,142 --> 00:48:10,323
He used to be a dragon.

1042
00:48:10,803 --> 00:48:13,544
But see, the gameplay is actually identical.

1043
00:48:13,744 --> 00:48:15,184
And then there being the Gorilla Boss.

1044
00:48:16,224 --> 00:48:17,325
This one is even more striking.

1045
00:48:17,405 --> 00:48:18,705
It's really, really respected.

1046
00:48:19,725 --> 00:48:21,946
So the timings, the size, the gameplay,

1047
00:48:22,026 --> 00:48:23,766
everything is really common.

1048
00:48:25,518 --> 00:48:27,238
checked first and

1049
00:48:27,399 --> 00:48:32,600
What's nice about this is that it means that you really kind of creating gameplay with a really small set of people as well

1050
00:48:33,300 --> 00:48:37,542
So that you know in terms of reviewing it tweaking and making sure that we are okay gameplay wise

1051
00:48:37,882 --> 00:48:40,403
It's done between you know like half, you know half a dozen people

1052
00:48:40,443 --> 00:48:44,844
That's it and then after that meanwhile the artists are busy researching how to make things

1053
00:48:45,224 --> 00:48:49,066
But they don't work on the game on those prototypes directly once it's proven

1054
00:48:49,326 --> 00:48:53,167
Then we open the doors and then you know, it becomes a more classic on a production relationship

1055
00:48:54,527 --> 00:48:55,348
And then finally, visuals.

1056
00:48:55,368 --> 00:48:59,994
So to be honest, it could have been a talk, an entire talk.

1057
00:49:00,374 --> 00:49:02,016
I'm just going to touch on three topics that seem

1058
00:49:02,036 --> 00:49:02,998
important to me as visuals.

1059
00:49:04,259 --> 00:49:07,543
We created, you know, we have a lot of organic levels,

1060
00:49:07,603 --> 00:49:11,448
but we wanted to retain the sci-fi DNA of the playroom

1061
00:49:11,468 --> 00:49:12,008
and those robots.

1062
00:49:12,048 --> 00:49:14,611
So we put a lot of printed circuit boards on organic stuff.

1063
00:49:15,582 --> 00:49:17,484
Also, the levels, we didn't want to have to worry

1064
00:49:17,524 --> 00:49:18,785
about making so much art,

1065
00:49:18,805 --> 00:49:20,968
because when you look down a level,

1066
00:49:21,008 --> 00:49:22,549
you can see to infinity in VR,

1067
00:49:22,569 --> 00:49:24,571
so we didn't want to have to worry about that.

1068
00:49:24,611 --> 00:49:25,672
So we made Floating Island.

1069
00:49:25,692 --> 00:49:27,194
We did study that at the beginning of the project,

1070
00:49:27,774 --> 00:49:29,556
and then we created a nice cloud shader.

1071
00:49:29,636 --> 00:49:31,297
So the cloud shader is animated.

1072
00:49:31,958 --> 00:49:33,379
We put quite a bit of effort into it,

1073
00:49:33,520 --> 00:49:37,423
but it could save 20 levels or something like that.

1074
00:49:38,024 --> 00:49:40,046
So that was a good investment for the return that we got.

1075
00:49:41,488 --> 00:49:46,410
The characters, so the way we go about it is that they're kind of cute mechanical designs

1076
00:49:46,710 --> 00:49:49,811
and you know you can get really close to them in VR and it's really important to have that

1077
00:49:49,831 --> 00:49:55,292
kind of endearing feeling but also we pay attention to the details so that you know

1078
00:49:55,312 --> 00:49:58,193
you can see all the cogs and all the parts and if we wanted to make toys out of them

1079
00:49:58,233 --> 00:49:59,073
we could easily do it.

1080
00:50:00,353 --> 00:50:01,934
That's why they have this kind of tangible feeling.

1081
00:50:03,115 --> 00:50:07,299
And the same thing goes for the gadgets.

1082
00:50:07,359 --> 00:50:09,581
They have the same kind of degree of fantasy about them,

1083
00:50:09,621 --> 00:50:11,623
but they're all inspired from real-life tools as well.

1084
00:50:12,124 --> 00:50:14,726
So like water guns, shurikens, slingshots, machine guns,

1085
00:50:15,006 --> 00:50:16,828
lights, they're all kind of real objects.

1086
00:50:16,868 --> 00:50:18,910
And so we're able to kind of really ground them.

1087
00:50:18,930 --> 00:50:23,135
And the parts are designed as if they were real products,

1088
00:50:23,575 --> 00:50:25,177
so that you can look at them closely in VR

1089
00:50:25,237 --> 00:50:26,438
and you can see all the little parts.

1090
00:50:29,674 --> 00:50:31,595
Okay, so that was visual and that's it for us.

1091
00:50:31,715 --> 00:50:34,617
But no, because we have a special section.

1092
00:50:35,057 --> 00:50:35,958
I think that's gonna be the one

1093
00:50:35,998 --> 00:50:38,179
that you guys have most fun about, right?

1094
00:50:38,219 --> 00:50:39,480
This is all the fails on the project.

1095
00:50:40,520 --> 00:50:43,102
So the game was multiplayer to begin with, actually.

1096
00:50:43,582 --> 00:50:44,643
So it started as multiplayer,

1097
00:50:45,163 --> 00:50:47,844
and it was one VR player and three players on the TV.

1098
00:50:47,884 --> 00:50:50,006
So that was a continuation of what we did on Playroom VR.

1099
00:50:50,846 --> 00:50:51,566
And it was really fun.

1100
00:50:51,586 --> 00:50:53,207
It was so much fun, you know, playing four players.

1101
00:50:55,148 --> 00:50:55,329
But.

1102
00:50:56,559 --> 00:50:58,424
The TV camera's range being limited,

1103
00:50:58,705 --> 00:51:01,432
the level designer could not exploit the VR properly.

1104
00:51:02,655 --> 00:51:04,620
So what you had was a lot of stuff like that, corridors.

1105
00:51:06,971 --> 00:51:08,831
And when he was in corridors, he was a little bit more open,

1106
00:51:08,851 --> 00:51:09,812
but it was still a corridor.

1107
00:51:11,352 --> 00:51:13,632
And so many levels felt like that.

1108
00:51:13,853 --> 00:51:15,233
Bosses, however, they worked really well,

1109
00:51:15,293 --> 00:51:16,293
because they were single screen.

1110
00:51:17,153 --> 00:51:19,654
So you can do that on the TV, and you can do that in VR.

1111
00:51:20,014 --> 00:51:21,894
As long as your camera angle on the TV

1112
00:51:21,914 --> 00:51:23,375
can show that big boss, then you're good.

1113
00:51:24,375 --> 00:51:26,175
So that was a four-player version of the bosses.

1114
00:51:26,715 --> 00:51:30,536
And so in the end, we also tried to do some mini-games separated

1115
00:51:30,576 --> 00:51:32,797
from the main game, because we didn't

1116
00:51:32,817 --> 00:51:33,997
want to have to throw all that stuff away.

1117
00:51:34,037 --> 00:51:36,498
It's really good to have people having a laugh.

1118
00:51:37,499 --> 00:51:41,163
And really, every morning we were having a blast playing the game together and it was so fun, right?

1119
00:51:42,185 --> 00:51:47,151
But then clearly we were making the wrong game because we were focusing on multiplayer at the expense of VR.

1120
00:51:47,651 --> 00:51:51,156
So all the stuff I talked about today, the VRness, the verticality, all of that, we couldn't do it

1121
00:51:51,216 --> 00:51:54,580
because the camera on the TV wouldn't allow us to follow the action.

1122
00:51:55,814 --> 00:51:59,856
So we decided to separate both of them to rebalance the game.

1123
00:51:59,936 --> 00:52:02,858
And in fact, it was effectively a cancellation of multiplayer.

1124
00:52:02,918 --> 00:52:05,220
It happened halfway through the game, so nine months

1125
00:52:05,260 --> 00:52:06,001
into the 18 months.

1126
00:52:07,301 --> 00:52:10,404
And that meant that, to be honest,

1127
00:52:10,604 --> 00:52:12,425
the levels we had after nine months were not that good.

1128
00:52:13,145 --> 00:52:15,487
So from that nine months onwards,

1129
00:52:15,587 --> 00:52:17,869
then the designers were able to focus on VR properly.

1130
00:52:18,349 --> 00:52:20,791
And then we started seeing some real good VR levels

1131
00:52:20,831 --> 00:52:21,271
coming through.

1132
00:52:21,831 --> 00:52:23,653
And after that, the level design really took off.

1133
00:52:25,776 --> 00:52:27,757
Um, yeah, and then other kind of, uh,

1134
00:52:27,977 --> 00:52:30,099
quick selection of components that we prototyped and cut.

1135
00:52:30,299 --> 00:52:31,780
And then often because they were not fun,

1136
00:52:31,960 --> 00:52:33,041
really hard to fit in the game,

1137
00:52:33,141 --> 00:52:34,942
or they were, like, not in line with the IP.

1138
00:52:35,082 --> 00:52:36,863
I don't know. Maybe you can guess which one that was.

1139
00:52:38,344 --> 00:52:40,925
Um, but, uh, yeah, gadgets and stuff like that.

1140
00:52:40,945 --> 00:52:43,687
So, you know, we cut quite a bit of content as well.

1141
00:52:45,076 --> 00:52:47,139
And also we did an art direction reboot.

1142
00:52:47,300 --> 00:52:50,605
That happened about the same time as the multiplayer.

1143
00:52:51,266 --> 00:52:54,131
The style was too kiddy, too, you know, it was colorful,

1144
00:52:54,171 --> 00:52:56,494
but it was the kind of wrong kind of colorful.

1145
00:52:57,852 --> 00:53:00,715
And so at that time, we had the same kind of review,

1146
00:53:00,775 --> 00:53:02,816
and we thought, OK, let's take it down a route of,

1147
00:53:02,836 --> 00:53:04,537
you know, it's playful, but it should remain

1148
00:53:04,578 --> 00:53:06,079
kind of sophisticated, cool.

1149
00:53:06,559 --> 00:53:08,841
You know, PSVR owners are gamers,

1150
00:53:09,141 --> 00:53:11,183
and their reference points are very high.

1151
00:53:11,263 --> 00:53:16,006
So yeah, we went down for a more mature look,

1152
00:53:16,126 --> 00:53:17,568
but we kept all the playfulness still.

1153
00:53:19,769 --> 00:53:20,290
OK, that's it.

1154
00:53:20,530 --> 00:53:23,472
So there's a few final thoughts for me, and I think for time.

1155
00:53:24,921 --> 00:53:25,761
Yeah, we're good.

1156
00:53:25,841 --> 00:53:32,123
So first of all, so the game became quite popular.

1157
00:53:32,163 --> 00:53:33,443
We had some really nice reviews.

1158
00:53:34,543 --> 00:53:38,384
And part of me is thinking that perhaps it

1159
00:53:38,424 --> 00:53:42,205
is because it's a nice mix of nostalgia and high technology.

1160
00:53:42,585 --> 00:53:47,866
It is a game that, and I'm not going to make any lies about it,

1161
00:53:47,986 --> 00:53:51,047
it's taking into 30 years of platform game history.

1162
00:53:51,107 --> 00:53:51,887
It is pop culture.

1163
00:53:51,907 --> 00:53:53,108
We all grew up with those games, 2D, 3D.

1164
00:53:54,708 --> 00:54:01,774
And so I think the fact that it's tapping into this nostalgia plus the addition of the coolness of VR,

1165
00:54:01,814 --> 00:54:07,219
I think it is perhaps what made it stand out as a kid's dream.

1166
00:54:07,299 --> 00:54:11,382
Perhaps it is the kind of game that we used to visualize in our kids' heads when playing 2D 8-bit games.

1167
00:54:14,807 --> 00:54:18,269
The other thing, and that's probably the biggest revelation, that's more of a personal thing, but

1168
00:54:19,911 --> 00:54:21,892
you know, we started the project and I was telling you that

1169
00:54:23,333 --> 00:54:26,636
it was all about, I remember being at GDC in fact, you know

1170
00:54:27,396 --> 00:54:30,439
being talked to by VR purists, experts, saying that

1171
00:54:31,059 --> 00:54:33,681
it had to be first person and virtual hands, or it wasn't VR.

1172
00:54:34,622 --> 00:54:42,170
But if you look at last year, you know, we had Moss, we had Tetris Effect, you had Astro Bot, before that it was Rez.

1173
00:54:42,190 --> 00:54:46,735
I think these are really, really great examples of classic games that have been reinvented for VR.

1174
00:54:47,636 --> 00:54:52,901
And so the point is to not copy and paste. It's not about taking those games and slapping them into VR.

1175
00:54:52,921 --> 00:54:56,305
I think we need to be able to deconstruct what was fun about these games in the 80s, 90s, 2000s.

1176
00:54:58,046 --> 00:55:02,591
And then reconstruct using our own words and our own technology.

1177
00:55:02,611 --> 00:55:04,653
And that's this very important point.

1178
00:55:04,673 --> 00:55:05,914
We often talk about that with the team.

1179
00:55:06,475 --> 00:55:09,538
It's not a copy and paste. It's an analysis and a reconstruction.

1180
00:55:11,928 --> 00:55:13,630
a non-VR version, so a lot of people come to us and say,

1181
00:55:13,650 --> 00:55:15,150
hey, why don't you just make a non-VR version?

1182
00:55:15,190 --> 00:55:16,851
Well, I think for the reasons I mentioned today,

1183
00:55:16,891 --> 00:55:18,312
it's like actually it was built for VR,

1184
00:55:18,372 --> 00:55:20,634
and so, you know, even if you played the game,

1185
00:55:20,694 --> 00:55:22,175
actually, on a flat screen,

1186
00:55:22,195 --> 00:55:24,336
you'd probably fail at a lot of the gems

1187
00:55:24,436 --> 00:55:26,978
because it was built for that 3Dness,

1188
00:55:27,018 --> 00:55:27,838
it was built for VR.

1189
00:55:28,799 --> 00:55:30,520
So if it was a non-VR game, it'd be a different game.

1190
00:55:33,340 --> 00:55:35,562
And that's it. So I just want to take a chance also to celebrate the team.

1191
00:55:37,063 --> 00:55:40,125
Astrobot was put together in 18 months with almost no other time, which is

1192
00:55:41,386 --> 00:55:42,407
very, very rare in Japan.

1193
00:55:43,548 --> 00:55:46,731
And in a fun mood, and I think we could get a good platformer out against the odds.

1194
00:55:47,311 --> 00:55:48,731
And it gives me a lot of hope for VR,

1195
00:55:48,771 --> 00:55:52,993
because many classic genres can be reinvented.

1196
00:55:53,253 --> 00:55:54,613
Adventure, racing, fighting.

1197
00:55:55,313 --> 00:55:59,194
If we apply the same approach, I think it's totally doable.

1198
00:55:59,234 --> 00:56:01,535
So if you're thinking about it, really go for it.

1199
00:56:02,075 --> 00:56:03,176
Just ask yourself the right questions.

1200
00:56:03,216 --> 00:56:05,516
And I think, I want to see an adventure game.

1201
00:56:05,556 --> 00:56:08,777
I want to see a Metrovania kind of game in VR.

1202
00:56:08,797 --> 00:56:09,477
That would be really cool.

1203
00:56:09,497 --> 00:56:13,118
All right, so that was all from me.

1204
00:56:13,598 --> 00:56:14,399
Thank you for listening today.

1205
00:56:14,419 --> 00:56:15,359
Have a great time at GDC.

1206
00:56:15,379 --> 00:56:15,559
Thank you.

